Plasm is **several MCP tools**; use what you need, in order. **`plasm_context`** opens one logical session; **`plasm`** returns a **dry-run plan** for programs inside it; **`plasm_run`** performs **live execution** after you review that plan; **`discover_capabilities`** finds **`api`** and **`entity`** values that match your intent when you do not already know them. **Skip `discover_capabilities`** when you already know every **`api`/`entity`** pair you need.
     **`discover_capabilities`**: pass **`query`** as one short string (what the user wants) or as several strings. The reply is a small fenced **table**: **`api`** (which integration), **`entity`** (which resource type there), **`description`**. Each row is one **capability pick** — use them to fill **`plasm_context`**’s **`seeds`** array (same columns per object).
     **`plasm_context`**: pass a stable **`intent`** string and a non-empty **`seeds`** array. Each object is **one capability pick**: **`api`** names the integration, **`entity`** names the resource type (same shape as discovery rows). **List every pick your program needs on the first call**—if the task spans more than one integration, put **all** picks in the **same** **`seeds`** array; that is still **one** session and **one** program surface for **`plasm`** / **`plasm_run`**. You may use **`entry_id`** instead of **`api`** on each object. Do not shrink **`seeds`** to “narrow” the session, and do not rotate **`intent`** every user message.
     **Adding picks:** call again when you discover **additional** capability picks you did not know at open time (append new `{api, entity}` rows—still additive).
     **Symbols:** authoritative **`e#` / `m#` / `p#`** appear in **`plasm_context`** replies that **open** the execute session, **append** new picks, or **recover** after a stale/expired binding (see **`_meta.plasm`**). **Steady state:** reuse **`logical_session_ref`** with **`plasm`** / **`plasm_run`**—do **not** loop **`plasm_context`** with identical **`seeds`** just to re-fetch DOMAIN; those no-op calls return a short notice **without** repeating the full teaching table (token-saving). If chat history lost the DOMAIN, rely on tool transcripts or open a new logical session / wait for continuity recovery—not gratuitous same-seed refresh.
     When several distinct **`api`** values load, one primary **`api`** orders the teaching block (alphabetically smallest name); symbols for every loaded capability stay in **one** program surface.
     **`plasm`**: pass **`logical_session_ref`** and one **`program`** string.
**JSON `program` string:** Use literal newline characters (U+000A) between statements when you have more than one binding—typically one `ident = …` per line, then bare comma-separated roots on the last line(s). Spaces do not separate statements. (Wire JSON may show `\n`; the parsed string must still contain real newlines.)

**Heredoc:** After `<<TAG` on the opener line, start the body on the next line; close with a line whose trimmed text is `TAG` (or `TAG)` / `TAG,` / `TAG}`). First trimmed-line match closes the heredoc—use a long opaque `TAG` for unconstrained payloads (MIME, markdown, logs).

Full grammar, bracket-render over `rows`, and `.content` rules: see **Plasm syntax guide** in MCP initialize instructions.
     **`plasm`** is **plan-only** (no live HTTP). Prefer **one** multi-line **`program`** per call for joins/reports/writes. Multi-root answers: review with **`plasm`**, execute with **`plasm_run`**. Never prefix roots with `return`.
     **`plasm_run`**: same arguments as **`plasm`**. Call **only after** the **`plasm`** dry-run plan matches intent—this tool performs **live** HTTP/API execution (and may return run snapshot URIs).
     **Paging:** follow **`page(s0_pgN)`** / `_meta.plasm.paging` in the same logical session for more rows.
     **Run snapshots:** `plasm://…` URIs are MCP **`resources/read`** targets, not Plasm expressions — call **`resources/read`** for full JSON when the summary points there.


Plasm syntax guide:

Follow the grammar and the teaching TSV below; reply with one valid plasm_program:

Output:
- Emit only code: either one `plasm_expr`, or one multi-line `plasm_program` with bindings then final roots.
- Do not emit prose, JSON wrappers, `return`, Markdown fences, or table rows.
- Prefer bind → narrow/project/transform → few final roots when more than one step is needed.

TSV table semantics:
- Header is exactly `plasm_expr<TAB>Meaning`; every following row has exactly one tab delimiter.
- Left cell is either executable syntax or metadata. Right cell is selection guidance only; never copy `Meaning` into output.
- Executable rows start with an entity surface (`e#`/`Entity`). Copy their left-cell shape, then replace placeholders.
- Metadata rows whose left cell is only `v#`/`value domain` define reusable value types. Metadata rows whose left cell is only `p#`/`field` define keyed slots. Metadata rows are never executable roots.
- `Meaning` fragments joined by ` · ` stay inside `Meaning`; they are not operators.

Symbol and fill rules:
- `e#` = entity surface; `m#` = method/action surface; `p#` = keyed field/parameter/relation slot; `v#` = value-domain metadata only.
- Entity-ref slots in `Meaning` look like `ref:Zone · str · Zone identifier`: canonical entity, id wire type, short note — not `plasm_expr` syntax.
- Never write `v#` inside a `plasm_expr`. Use `p#` keys in code and use `v#` rows only to understand allowed values/types.
- `$` appears only in taught examples as a required fill placeholder. Replace every `$`; never emit `$`.
- `<id>`, `<value>`, `<receiver>`, and `elem` in this contract are meta-variables, not syntax tokens.
- If a copied row contains `..`, it is an ellipsis for omitted optional keys. Remove `..` or replace it with additional `p#=<value>` assignments before final output.
- If `Meaning` says `optional params: pA, pB`, those keys may be added only as keyed assignments with real values.
- Projection rows ending `[p#,…]` teach a valid field set. Reuse that suffix only on another expression returning the same entity or list type.
- Relation rows end with `.p#`/`.field`; apply them to any executable receiver row for that same entity type.
- `page(sN_pgM)` uses a continuation handle returned by a prior response; copy the handle exactly and optionally add `, limit=N`.

Grammar:
plasm_program ::= plasm_expr | binding+ roots
binding       ::= ident "=" node
roots         ::= root ("," root)*
root          ::= ident | plasm_expr
node          ::= (plasm_expr | ident) postfix* render_tail? | ident "=>" value_or_template
plasm_expr    ::= entity_expr [projection] | page
entity_expr   ::= query_all | get | query | relation | method | create_action | search
query_all     ::= e#
get           ::= e#(<id>) or e#(p#=<value>, p#=<value>)
query         ::= e#{p#=<value>, …}
relation      ::= <receiver>.p#
method        ::= e#(<id>).m#() or e#(<id>).m#(p#=<value>, …)
create_action ::= e#.m#(p#=<value>, …)
search        ::= e#~"text"
page          ::= page(sN_pgM) | page(sN_pgM, limit=N)
projection    ::= e#(<id>)[p#,…] | "[" fields "]"
postfix       ::= ".limit(N)" | ".page_size(N)" | ".sort(field[, dir])" | ".aggregate(specs)" | ".group_by(field, specs)" | ".singleton()" | "[" fields "]"
render_tail   ::= ("[" fields "]")? "<<TAG" template_body "TAG"
fields        ::= [p#,…]
specs         ::= name=count | name=sum(field) | name=avg(field) | name=min(field) | name=max(field) [, ...]
dir           ::= desc | asc | descending | ascending
value_or_template ::= literal | ident | ident.field | _.field | [elem, ...] | heredoc
literal       ::= quoted string | number | bool | null

Composition rules:
- Multi-line program strings use literal newlines: one binding per line, final roots last. Spaces never separate statements.
- Postfix transforms and `[fields]` may chain on any bound node or expression that returns rows.
- Render tails use Minijinja over `rows`; the render result is one row with `content`. Pass `binding.content` to string/body parameters.
- Heredoc opener `<<TAG` is followed by newline; the first later line whose trimmed text is `TAG` closes it. Choose a tag not present in the body.
- Examples: scoped child list `e#{p#=e#(<id>)}`; array argument `p#=[e#(<id>), …]`. Quoted strings use only `\"` and `\\` escapes.
- `markdown`/`html`/`document`/`json_text`/`blob` values (per `Meaning`): `<<TAG` … `TAG` only; e.g. `m#(..., p#=<<TXT` + newline body + `TXT` newline `)`.
